theorem P3_closed_iff_isOpen {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X}
    (hA : IsClosed A) : Topology.P3 A ↔ IsOpen A := by
  dsimp [Topology.P3]
  constructor
  · intro hP3
    -- From `P3` we obtain `A ⊆ interior (closure A)`.
    -- Since `A` is closed, `closure A = A`, so we actually have `A ⊆ interior A`.
    have hSubset : (A : Set X) ⊆ interior A := by
      simpa [hA.closure_eq] using hP3
    -- The reverse inclusion `interior A ⊆ A` is always true.
    have hSuperset : interior A ⊆ (A : Set X) := interior_subset
    -- Hence `A = interior A`, and `A` is open.
    have hEq : (A : Set X) = interior A :=
      Set.Subset.antisymm_iff.mpr ⟨hSubset, hSuperset⟩
    have : IsOpen (interior A) := isOpen_interior
    simpa [hEq] using this
  · intro hOpen
    -- Because `A` is open and closed, `interior A = A`
    -- and `closure A = A`. Thus `A ⊆ interior (closure A)` holds.
    have hIntEq : interior A = (A : Set X) := hOpen.interior_eq
    have hClosEq : closure A = (A : Set X) := hA.closure_eq
    have : (A : Set X) ⊆ A := subset_rfl
    simpa [hIntEq, hClosEq] using this

theorem interior_nonempty_of_P1 {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X}
    (hP1 : Topology.P1 A) (hne : A.Nonempty) : (interior A).Nonempty := by
  classical
  -- Assume, for a contradiction, that `interior A` is empty.
  by_contra hInt
  have hIntEq : interior A = (∅ : Set X) := by
    apply Set.eq_empty_iff_forall_not_mem.mpr
    intro x hx
    have : (interior A).Nonempty := ⟨x, hx⟩
    exact (hInt this).elim
  -- Pick an element of `A`.
  rcases hne with ⟨x, hxA⟩
  -- Use `P1` to map it into the closure of the interior.
  have hxClosure : x ∈ closure (interior A) := hP1 hxA
  -- Contradiction with the fact that the interior is empty.
  have : x ∈ (∅ : Set X) := by
    simpa [hIntEq] using hxClosure
  exact (Set.not_mem_empty x) this
